According to scientists, the phenomenon is directly linked to global warming AUSTRALIA - New aerial surveys show more than two-thirds of the coral in Australia's Great Barrier Reef is experiencing 'shocking' amounts of bleaching.Coral bleaching is a stress response that happens during an increase in sea temperaturesAccording to scientists, the phenomenon is directly linked to global warming.Marine Biologist Professor Sean Connolly said: &quot;In 2016 we had by far the most serious mass bleaching event, ever. Mass bleaching really only started after climate change started influencing sea temperatures in the 1980s. So this is a new phenomenon and it is getting worse.&quot; (Edited by Refilwe Thobega)